{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a51ac79b-a415-4b6b-ab76-cc597a3d2afb","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK needed. Inside the container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Other options:**\n- For **ARM64** containers, use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64` in the URL.\n- You can also `docker cp` the binary in from the host instead of curling inside the container.\n- Convert to Speedscope format for viewing: add `--format speedscope` to the collect command.\n- To limit collection duration, add `--duration 00:00:30` (30 seconds).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f36c7d2-454d-405e-9fc2-584d852b8dea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version directly.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"2C4F:2DA8C:148972F:174463C:69F947C6"},"id":"7f075299-8dec-449a-b65f-1f6418192af0","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:28:48.262Z","parentId":"274b0ccb-59d4-4719-90f1-35c1210479f0"}
